         <div type="edition"><!-- transcription goes here -->
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>D<hi rend="tall">i</hi>s Manibus 
               <lb n="2"/>sacrum 
               <lb n="3"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Arria">Arriae</name>
                  <persName>
                     <name type="praenomen" key="Caius">
                        <expan><abbr>C</abbr><ex>aii</ex></expan>
                     </name>
                  </persName>
                  <expan><abbr>l</abbr><ex>ibertae</ex></expan>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Clamys">Clam<hi rend="tall">y</hi>s</name></persName>. 
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
             <p>Sacred to the divine spirits of Arria Clamys, freedwoman of Gaius.</p>
            <p/>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary"><!-- notes go here -->
             <p>Line 1: tall I in Dis</p>
           <p>Line 3: tall Y in Clamys</p>
             <p>Clamys (nominative) for C(h)lamydis (genitive) or C(h)lamidi (dative). The mixture of nomen or praenomen in an oblique case followed by cognomen in the nominative is not uncommon. The Greek name "C(h)lamys" is not attested elsewhere but belongs to a well recognized category of Roman slave names derived from terms for clothing: see H. Solin, Di stadtrömischen Sklavennamen. Ein Namenbuch (Stuttgart 1996) 166, 536. The text is construed differently by G. Crimi (in Syll. Epigr. Barc., 15, 2017) and A. Ferraro at EDR158071 (07-10-2017), followed by EDCS-72300123, who understand the name in the nominative case and correct "Arriae" accordingly. We construe the text as a single syntactical unit.</p>
            <p/>
         </div>
